=={{flag|Algeria}}==
A first case of swine influenza was detected in Algeria on June 20. This was an Algerian national, resident in [[Frankfurt]] and coming from [[Miami]] with her two children.

This first case was detected at [[Houari Boumediene Airport]]. Many Algerian immigrants and tourists were arriving during this holiday period, increasing the risk of spreading the virus. The woman suffering from flu was immediately transferred to the hospital of El-Kettar’ in [[Algiers]].<ref>http://www.ennaharonline.com/en/news/1491.html</ref>

=={{flag|Benin}}==
As of May 2, 2009 there was one suspected case of swine flu in [[Benin]].<ref>[http://www.thetimes.co.za/News/Article.aspx?id=991159 Swine flue confirmed in Benin], The Times, May 2, 2009. Accessed 2009-08-03.  [http://www.webcitation.org/5jeIDyLiG Archived] 2009-09-08.</ref>

=={{flag|Egypt}}==
The Egyptian government increased numbers of medical officers at [[Cairo Airport]] and pledged to monitor passengers from Mexico during their stay.<ref name=bbc1>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/8022516.stm#americas The world response to flu crisis], BBC News, 2009-04-28. Retrieved on 2009-04-30.</ref>

The government ordered the mass slaughter of all pigs in Egypt on April 29,<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/04/30/2556545.htm?section=justin Egypt orders pig cull], ABC News, 2009-04-30. Retrieved on 2009-04-30. [http://www.webcitation.org/5jeIFP7NS Archived] 2009-09-08.</ref> even though the pandemic strain was a human-human transmittable, human influenza that has already previously hybridized with avian and swine flu.<ref name=food>{{cite news | first= | last= | coauthors= |authorlink= | title=OIE position on safety of international trade of pigs and products of pig origin | date=April 28, 2009 | publisher=World Organization for Animal Health | url =http://www.oie.int/eng/press/en_090428.htm | work = | pages = | accessdate = 2009-04-30 | language = |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5jeIFpFt1|archivedate=2009-09-08|deadurl=no}}</ref> The [[World Organization for Animal Health]] called the swine killing "scientifically unjustified".<ref name=food />

Egypt commenced the slaughter on 2 May 2009.<ref name="Iraq culls three wild pigs at Baghdad zoo">{{cite web|url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jVxwhffSW4vItUaza1MCp6cgrbew|title=Iraq culls three wild pigs at Baghdad zoo|date=2009-04-03|accessdate=2009-05-04|publisher=[[Google]]}}</ref>
On the next day in [[Cairo]], an estimated 300 Coptic Christian residents of the [[Manshiyat Nasr]] district set up blockades on the street in attempt to keep government officers from confiscating their pigs,<ref name=Compass_Direct_News>{{cite news | url = http://compassdirect.org/en/display.php?page=news&idelement=5910&lang=en&length=short&backpage=index&critere=&countryname=&rowcur=50 | title = Egypt: swine destruction threatens coptic-run industry | date =2009-05-05 | publisher = Compass Direct News | accessdate= 15 June 2009 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> which led to clashes with the police.<ref name=BBC_Egypt>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/8031490.stm|title=Clashes erupt over Egypt pig cull |date=2009-05-03|publisher=BBC News| accessdate =2009-05-03| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090505033159/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/8031490.stm| archivedate= 5 May 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>  ''[[Al-Ahram]]'', a widely circulated Egyptian newspaper, reported that owners of destroyed pigs would receive 1000 [[Egyptian pound]]s (approximately US$177.70) per animal in compensation,<ref name=Reuters_Egypt>{{cite news | title = UN agency slams Egypt order to cull all pigs | url = http://www.reuters.com/article/europeCrisis/idUSLT11250 | first = Phil | last = Stewart | publisher = Reuters | date = 2009-04-29 | accessdate= 15 June 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090503034026/http://www.reuters.com/article/europeCrisis/idUSLT11250| archivedate= 3 May 2009| deadurl= no}}</ref> but [[Reuters]] reported that the issue was still "under discussion", citing an Egyptian cabinet spokesman.<ref name=Reuters_Egypt/>

The first case of the novel H1N1 virus was discovered in Cairo, Egypt on the second of June, in a 12-year-old girl coming from the USA with her mother. Only the girl was infected, and the officials caught the case before she left the airport.

A second and third case were discovered on Sunday 7 June: two students at the [[American University of Cairo]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://af.reuters.com/article/topNews/idAFJOE5510ED20090602 | work=Reuters | title=Egypt detects first H1N1 flu case: WHO official | date=2 June 2009| accessdate= 15 June 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090605174842/http://af.reuters.com/article/topNews/idAFJOE5510ED20090602| archivedate= 5 June 2009| deadurl= no}}</ref>

As of June 9, there were 8 confirmed case of swine flu in Egypt.

On June 11, 2 more cases were discovered, along with 2 cases discovered a day earlier, bringing the total number of swine flu cases to 12.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iP1qStvCULJ_rKgmloiXfwbJcKGA|title=Toddler latest swine flu case in Egypt|accessdate=2009-06-12| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090616125702/http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iP1qStvCULJ_rKgmloiXfwbJcKGA| archivedate= 16 June 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

As of December 3, the confirmed cases were 3558 and the deaths 24.
As of January 31, there were 258 confirmed deaths from A/H1N1 influenza in [[Egypt]], and in excess of 15,800 confirmed cases of H1N1.<ref>http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/health/2010-02/01/c_13158226.htm</ref>

=={{flag|Ethiopia}}==
{{Out of date|date=December 2009}}
{{Expand section|date=December 2009}}
{{Update|date=December 2009}}
On June 19, 2009 the Ethiopian government reported two cases of swine flu.  They were both in girls who had returned from school in the United States for summer break.

=={{flag|Ghana}}==
{{Expand section|date=December 2009}}
Ghana banned the importation of pork and pork products.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gbcghana.com/news/25813detail.html|title=Ghana bans importation of pork and pork products |publisher=Ghana Broadcasting Corporation|date=2009-04-28|accessdate=2009-04-30|author=Ghana Broadcasting Corporation <!-- BOT GENERATED AUTHOR -->|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5jeJ8Z0nY|archivedate=2009-09-08|deadurl=no}}</ref>

=={{flag|Kenya}}==
{{Out of date|date=December 2009}}
{{Expand section|date=December 2009}}
Kenya health authorities started screening travellers at [[Jomo Kenyatta International Airport|Jomo Kenyatta]] and [[Moi International Airport|Moi international airports]] on April 28. Public Health and Sanitation minister Beth Mugo said travellers from Mexico, and those from Texas, California and New York were being screened.<ref>http://www.nation.co.ke/News/-/1056/592220/-/u65k7o/-/index.html</ref>

On June 29, a British medical student beame the first confirmed case of swine flu in Kenya. The student, who was in a group of 33, was in Kenya to attend a series of medical camps in Nyanza province. The whole group was quarantined in their hotel in [[Kisumu]] while undergoing treatment.

There was a panic in [[Nairobi]] as mobile text messages circulated warning people to stay away from Sarit centre, a popular commercial establishment where another suspected case had been diagnosed. The patient's test results however came back negative for the H1N1 virus.<ref>http://en.wikinews.org/wiki/Kenya_confirms_first_swine_flu_case</ref><ref>http://swineflu.ushahidi.com/reports/view/764</ref><ref>http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jlzMvITjfWhY0IePXScfbIeaoToA</ref>

=={{flag|Libya|1977}}==
{{Expand section|date=December 2009}}
On 6 July 2009, Libya had its first confirmed case of swine flu.

=={{flag|Morocco}}==
{{Expand section|date=December 2009}}
{{Out of date|date=December 2009}}
{{Update|date=December 2009}}
[[Morocco]] confirmed the first case of novel human swine flu (A/H1N1-2009) on 12 June, in an 18-year old university student returning from Canada.<ref>Reuters, [http://www.reuters.com/article/americasCrisis/idUSLC292881 "Morocco confirms first H1N1 flu case -ministry"], 12 June 2009 (accessed 14 June 2009)</ref>

=={{flag|Namibia}}==
[[Image:H1N1 Namibia map.png|thumb|right|200px|Outbreak evolution in Namibia{{legend|#000000|Deaths}}{{legend|#FF0000|Confirmed cases}}]]
Namibia confirmed its first two cases of swine flu on July 20.

Both cases involved young adults who had been traveling in other countries: a 13-year-old boy from [[Rehoboth, Namibia|Rehoboth]] who returned from a rugby trip with 20 other students in [[South Africa]] and a young student returning from Europe. The latter was taken by ambulance to hospital directly from the international airport in [[Windhoek]] as she showed severe signs of flu.<ref>http://www.sabcnews.com/portal/site/SABCNews/menuitem.5c4f8fe7ee929f602ea12ea1674daeb9/?vgnextoid=c3dbbe29a6992210VgnVCM10000077d4ea9bRCRD&vgnextfmt=default</ref>

=={{flag|Nigeria}}==
[[Nigeria]]n Health Minister [[Babatunde Osotimehin]] announced that the country was stockpiling antiviral treatments, informing the public and increasing surveillance.<ref name=bbc1/>

The first A/H1N1 death was confirmed in Nigeria on 5 January 2010, with the victim being a 38-year-old woman from Lagos who was infected in the US.

=={{flag|Tunisia}}==
[[Tunisia]] confirmed the two first cases of swine flu (A/H1N1-2009) on June 22. Both cases were returning from the United States, and recovered quickly.<ref>Associated Press, [http://fr.news.yahoo.com/3/20090622/twl-grippe-a-h1n1-tunisie-1be00ca.html "Grippe A/H1N1: deux premiers cas en Tunisie"], 22 June 2009 (accessed 22 June 2009)</ref>

=={{flag|South Africa}}==
{{Expand section|date=December 2009}}
[[Image:H1N1 South Africa Map.svg|thumb|right|200px|Outbreak evolution in South Africa {{legend|#000000|Deaths}}{{legend|#FF0000|Confirmed cases}}]]
On April 29, [[South Africa]] reported two possible cases of swine flu from two women who had recently travelled in Mexico.<ref name=news24>[http://www.news24.com/News24/South_Africa/News/0,,2-7-1442_2508746,00.html 2 suspected swine flu cases in SA], News24, April 29, 2009</ref> On June 18, the first case was confirmed. Later, on 29 June the South African National Department of Health confirmed 7 cases of swine influenza in the country.<ref name=MG>[http://www.mg.co.za/article/2009-06-29-seven-confirmed-cases-of-swine-flu-in-sa Seven Confirmed Cases of Swine Flu in SA], Mail & Guardian, June 29, 2009. Accessed 2009-08-03.  [http://www.webcitation.org/5jeJADY2i Archived] 2009-09-08.</ref>

The first death in South Africa was confirmed on 3 August. The victim was a student at the [[University of Stellenbosch]]. A few days later the second confirmed death was announced: a male in Durban, Mount Edgecombe<ref>{{cite web|title=Cape Times|url=http://www.capetimes.co.za/?fSectionId=&fArticleId=nw20090803143947888C413989|work=|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5jeJJrvGa|archivedate=2009-09-08|deadurl=no|accessdate=2009-08-03}}</ref>

The H1N1 virus was a concern for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]], which took place in June 2010.<ref>http://health.iafrica.com/healthnews/2256901.htm</ref><ref>http://www.goal.com/en/news/1863/world-cup-2010/2010/02/16/1793220/world-cup-2010-swine-flu-threat-in-mind</ref>

=={{flagicon|Sudan}} Sudan==
The first case of swine flu in Sudan was confirmed in mid July 2009.  At the end of November the first case was confirmed in Southern Sudan.<ref>[http://www.sudantribune.com/spip.php?article33344 ''Sudan Tribune'', Dec. 5, 2009]</ref>

As of December 28, 2009 there were five deaths and over 150 confirmed cases of swine flu in Sudan.<ref>[http://www.sudantribune.com/spip.php?article33613 ''Sudan Tribune'' Dec. 28, 2990]</ref>

=={{flag|Zambia}}==
An emergency task force was set up by the [[Government of Zambia|Zambian government]].<ref name=bbc1/>

